Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1251–1330":"1251–1330","1243–Female":"1243–Deceased","1249–1308":"1249–1308","1252–1314":"1252–1314","–Female":"Deceased","1265–1347":"1265–1347","1229–1279":"1229–1279","1226–1243":"1226–1243","1330":"1330","1252":"1252","1251":"1251","before 15 July 1279":"before 15 July 1279","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1347":"1347","1314":"1314","1279":"1279","1265":"1265","1243":"1243","about 1265":"about 1265","1308":"1308","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1229":"1229","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Whitby, Yorkshire, , England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mauley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Declan.","Irish: variant of   McCauley  . Compare the Scottish form   Macaulay  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Macaulay","meanings":["Scottish (mainly Ross and Cromarty and Inverness):","from Gaelic <b>Mac Amhalghaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Amhalghadh</i>’, an Old Gaelic personal name of unexplained etymology. Compare the Irish form   McAuley  , also Manx   Kewley  ,   Cowley  , and   Callow  .","from Gaelic <b>Mac Amhlaoibh</b> ‘son of <i>Amhlao(i)bh</i>’, Gaelic form of the Old Norse personal name <i>Óláfr</i> (see   Olafsen  ). Compare   McAuliffe  ."]},{"name":"McCamley","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: from Gaelic <b>Mac Camlaoich</b> ‘son of <i>Camlaoch</i>’, a personal name based on the words <i>cam</i> ‘bent’ and <i>laoch</i> ‘hero’. In some cases it may also be from Gaelic <b>Mac Amhalghaidh</b> or <b>Mac Amhlaoibh</b> (see   McAuley  ,   Macaulay  )."]},{"name":"McCauley","meanings":["Scottish (Dumbartonshire) and Irish (Westmeath): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Amhalghaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Amhalghadh</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin. The best known family of <i>Mac Amhalghaidh</i> is from Westmeath, and there were families called <i>Mac Amhlaoibh</i> in counties Cork and Fermanagh (a branch of the Maguires), as well as a family in southwest Scotland which has migrated to Ulster. Compare the Scottish form   Macaulay  .","Scottish (Hebrides) and Irish (Fermanagh): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Amhlaoibh</b> or <b>Mac Amhlaidh</b> ‘son of Olaf’, from Gaelic forms of the Old Norse personal name <i>Áleifr</i>, <i>Óláfr</i> (see   Olafsen  ). Compare   McAuliffe  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":8,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":39,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":64,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":77,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert de Mauley was born in 1251, in Whitby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Piers Maulay II, was 22 and his mother, Joan Brus, was 25. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs Robert de Mauley. He died in 1330, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 79."},"et":{"1251–1330":"1251–1330","1243–Female":"1243–Surnud","1249–1308":"1249–1308","1252–1314":"1252–1314","–Female":"Surnud","1